{"id":"1312.3154","submitter":"Barbara Ercolano Prof","authors":"B. Ercolano (USM-Munich, Exc-C Universe), D. Mayr (USM-Munich), J. E.\n  Owen (CITA), G. Rosotti (USM Munich, MPE), C. F. Manara (ESO)","title":"The Mdot - M* relation of pre-main sequence stars: a consequence of\n  X-ray driven disc evolution","comments":"9 pages, 6 Figures, 2 Tables, accepted by MNRAS","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1093/mnras/stt2405","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.SR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We analyse current measurements of accretion rates onto pre-main sequence\nstars as a function of stellar mass, and conclude that the steep dependance of\naccretion rates on stellar mass is real and not driven by selection/detection\nthreshold, as has been previously feared. These conclusions are reached by\nmeans of statistical tests including a survival analysis which can account for\nupper limits. The power-law slope of the Mdot-M* relation is found to be in the\nrange of 1.6-1.9 for young stars with masses lower than 1 Msun. The measured\nslopes and distributions can be easily reproduced by means of a simple disc\nmodel which includes viscous accretion and X-ray photoevaporation. We conclude\nthat the Mdot-M* relation in pre-main sequence stars bears the signature of\ndisc dispersal by X-ray photoevaporation, suggesting that the relation is a\nstraight- forward consequence of disc physics rather than an imprint of initial\nconditions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 11 Dec 2013 13:27:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-03-05"}
